UPDATE course_modules SET content = '## Overview

Cannabis transportation and delivery in Maryland involves the secure, compliant movement of medical cannabis products between licensed facilities (cultivators to processors, processors to dispensaries) and, under certain regulatory frameworks, potentially from dispensaries to patients'' homes. Every transfer requires meticulous documentation, specialized security protocols, real-time tracking through Maryland''s Metrc system, and strict adherence to COMAR transportation regulations designed to prevent diversion, theft, and public safety risks. For dispensary employees involved in receiving shipments, verifying transport manifests, or understanding how products reach your facility, transportation knowledge ensures you can identify discrepancies, maintain chain of custody, and contribute to secure supply chain integrity.

## Maryland Transportation Regulations

COMAR 10.62.33 establishes comprehensive transportation requirements for cannabis businesses:

**Licensed Transporter Requirements**: Only licensed cannabis businesses (cultivators, processors, dispensaries) or their designated employees may transport medical cannabis. Third-party courier services are NOT permitted unless specifically licensed by MCA as transporters. Employees transporting cannabis must carry their facility''s employee badge and authorization letter.

**Vehicle Requirements**: Transport vehicles must be owned, leased, or rented by the licensed cannabis business (no personal vehicles unless specifically approved), equipped with GPS tracking devices that log routes in real-time, contain secure, locked storage compartments permanently affixed to the vehicle, display no external markings or logos identifying them as cannabis transport vehicles (for security), and have commercial vehicle insurance meeting MCA requirements.

**Personnel Requirements**: At least two employees must be present during transport at all times—a driver and an observer. Single-person transports are prohibited for security reasons. Both individuals must be age 21+ and pass background checks. Both carry facility employee badges and authorization letters.

**Prohibited Circumstances**: Cannabis may not be transported in vehicles containing firearms or weapons (unless employees are licensed security personnel), may not be transported in vehicles used for personal purposes or non-cannabis cargo simultaneously, and may not be left unattended in vehicles for any reason—if the vehicle must be parked, both employees remain with it.

## Transport Manifests and Documentation

Every cannabis transfer requires a detailed transport manifest that accompanies the shipment:

**Manifest Contents**: The manifest (generated through Metrc system) includes: sender facility name, license number, and address; recipient facility name, license number, and address; departure date and time; estimated arrival date and time; detailed product inventory (strain names, batch numbers, quantities by weight, package counts, Metrc UID tags for each package); transporter names and employee IDs; vehicle description (make, model, license plate); and unique manifest number for tracking.

**Pre-Departure Procedures**: Before leaving the origin facility, the transport team verifies all products listed on the manifest are physically present in the vehicle, checks that Metrc UID tags match the manifest exactly, confirms all products are properly packaged and sealed, secures products in the vehicle''s locked storage compartment, and ensures the manifest is printed and carried during transport (plus digital copy in Metrc accessible via mobile device).

**During Transport**: Transporters follow the most direct route to the destination without unnecessary stops, maintain GPS tracking active throughout transport, keep the vehicle locked when not actively loading/unloading, and communicate any delays or incidents to both origin and destination facilities immediately.

**Arrival Procedures**: Upon arrival at the destination facility, receiving personnel verify the manifest against physical products delivered (count packages, check Metrc tags, compare to manifest), inspect all products for damage or tampering (check tamper-evident seals), document receipt in Metrc system in real-time, and both transporter and receiver sign the manifest acknowledging the successful transfer.

## Receiving Shipments at Dispensaries

Dispensary employees responsible for receiving inventory follow strict protocols:

**Before Unloading**: Verify the transport vehicle has appropriate markings (or lack thereof per regulations), check that two transport personnel are present, request to see employee badges and authorization letters, and confirm the manifest number matches the expected delivery.

**During Inspection**: Count every package delivered and compare to manifest quantity, scan or manually verify every Metrc UID tag matches the manifest, inspect packages for intact tamper-evident seals, check for signs of damage, contamination, or temperature exposure (for products requiring climate control), and weigh flower products to confirm quantities match labeled weights.

**Discrepancy Handling**: If you discover discrepancies (missing products, extra products, damaged items, mismatched Metrc tags), immediately halt the receiving process, notify the transporter and your dispensary manager, document the discrepancy thoroughly with photos if possible, do NOT sign the manifest until discrepancies are resolved, and follow your dispensary''s SOP for discrepancy investigation (may involve MCA notification).

**Finalizing Receipt**: Once all products are verified accurate and undamaged, sign the manifest confirming receipt, provide a copy to the transporter, upload the signed manifest to your dispensary''s records, and update inventory in your POS system to reflect newly received products.

## Chain of Custody and Metrc Integration

Maintaining unbroken chain of custody is critical to prevent diversion and ensure regulatory compliance:

**Metrc Transfer Creation**: When a cultivator or processor ships products, they create a transfer package in Metrc that generates the manifest and assigns unique tracking numbers. This electronically documents that specific products left their facility.

**Real-Time Updates**: Throughout transport, the Metrc system tracks the transfer status (in transit, delivered, rejected). Delays or incidents must be noted in Metrc immediately.

**Receipt Confirmation**: When the receiving dispensary accepts the shipment, they mark the transfer complete in Metrc—officially transferring custody of the products from the shipper to the receiver. Until this happens, the shipper remains responsible for the inventory.

**Audit Trail**: Metrc maintains a permanent record of every transfer, creating a seed-to-sale audit trail that MCA can review during inspections. Any gaps in the chain of custody (unexplained inventory losses, unsigned manifests, unrecorded transfers) are serious compliance violations.

## Emergency Protocols During Transport

Transport teams must prepare for potential emergencies:

**Vehicle Breakdown**: If the transport vehicle becomes inoperable, immediately secure all cannabis products, contact the origin and destination facilities to report the situation, arrange for a backup licensed transport vehicle (not a tow truck carrying the products unsecured), and remain with the products until transfer to the backup vehicle is complete. Document the incident thoroughly in Metrc and internal logs.

**Traffic Accident**: If involved in a traffic accident, ensure all personnel are safe and request emergency medical care if needed, secure the cannabis products and prevent unauthorized access, contact law enforcement (be prepared to show manifests and employee badges to demonstrate legal transport), notify origin and destination facilities immediately, and document the incident with photos, police report numbers, and witness information.

**Theft or Robbery**: If cannabis products are stolen during transport, immediately contact law enforcement and report the theft, notify MCA within required timeframes (typically 24 hours), document exactly what was stolen (refer to manifest), and cooperate fully with investigations. Do NOT attempt to confront or pursue thieves—your safety is paramount.

**Law Enforcement Stops**: If stopped by police during transport, remain calm and professional, immediately present your employee badge, authorization letter, and transport manifest, explain that you''re conducting legal cannabis transport under state license, provide the facility''s license number and contact information, and comply with officer instructions. Legal cannabis transport is permitted under Maryland law when properly documented.

## Best Practices for Secure Transport

**Route Planning**: Plan transport routes in advance to minimize travel time and avoid high-crime areas when possible, vary departure times and routes to prevent predictability (which could be exploited for robberies), and avoid transports during nighttime hours unless necessary.

**Communication Protocols**: Maintain communication between transport personnel and the origin/destination facilities, report arrival and departure times to facilities for tracking, and establish check-in protocols (e.g., contact facility if transport exceeds expected duration by more than 30 minutes).

**Security Awareness**: Monitor for vehicles following the transport vehicle, be vigilant for suspicious activity around the vehicle during stops, and never discuss transport contents, routes, or schedules in public or on unsecured communication channels.

**Vehicle Maintenance**: Ensure transport vehicles are well-maintained and unlikely to break down, conduct pre-trip inspections (tires, fluids, lights, GPS functionality), and keep emergency supplies (first aid kit, flashlight, phone chargers) in vehicles.

## Delivery to Patients (If Authorized)

Some states allow dispensaries to deliver cannabis directly to patients'' homes. If Maryland implements delivery regulations (currently limited), strict protocols will apply:

**Patient Verification**: Delivery drivers must verify patient MMCC registration cards and photo IDs at the delivery location before handing over products—identical to in-dispensary verification procedures. No products may be left on doorsteps or delivered to anyone other than the registered patient or caregiver.

**Secure Transport**: Products must remain in locked storage within the delivery vehicle until hand-off to the verified patient. Delivery vehicles require GPS tracking and secure compartments just like facility-to-facility transports.

**Age-Restricted Locations**: Deliveries may be prohibited near schools, playgrounds, or other age-restricted areas—delivery drivers must confirm addresses are permissible.

**Transaction Recording**: Deliveries must be recorded in the POS system in real-time with all required information (just like in-dispensary sales). Delivery drivers typically use mobile POS devices or tablets with cellular data connectivity.

## Common Challenges & Solutions

**Challenge**: Manifest shows 20 packages but only 19 are delivered.  
**Solution**: Do NOT sign the manifest. Immediately contact the transporter and their origin facility to investigate. Document the missing package with photos of what was delivered. Hold the shipment until the discrepancy is resolved—either the missing package is located and delivered, or the manifest is corrected to reflect the actual delivery.

**Challenge**: Package tamper-evident seal is broken on one product.  
**Solution**: Quarantine that package immediately—do not accept it into your inventory. Document the tampering with photos. Notify the sender and your manager. Follow your SOP for damaged or compromised products (likely return to sender for investigation or disposal).

**Challenge**: Transporter arrives alone (single person) instead of the required two-person team.  
**Solution**: Refuse the delivery and send the transporter back. Single-person transports violate COMAR regulations and create liability for both the sender and your dispensary if accepted. Document the refused delivery and report it to management for follow-up with the sending facility.

**Challenge**: GPS tracking system malfunctions during transport.  
**Solution**: Transport personnel notify both facilities immediately and document the malfunction. Depending on dispensary SOPs, transport may need to return to origin until GPS is repaired, or continue with increased communication check-ins and incident documentation. Never ignore GPS failures—they''re compliance violations.

## Conclusion

Cannabis transportation is far more than simply driving products from Point A to Point B—it''s a highly regulated, security-intensive process that maintains the integrity of Maryland''s medical cannabis supply chain and prevents diversion to illegal markets. For dispensary employees receiving shipments, your vigilance in verifying manifests, inspecting products, and maintaining chain of custody protects your facility from compliance violations and ensures patients receive safe, tracked, and properly documented medicine. Every manifest you verify, every Metrc tag you scan, and every discrepancy you catch contributes to the security and legitimacy of Maryland''s medical cannabis program. Take this responsibility seriously—your attention to detail in receiving operations is the final checkpoint before products reach patients.'
WHERE module_number = 16;